<!-- ─── Overview ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<div style="margin-bottom: 32px; padding: 20px; background: #f0f7ff; border: 1px solid #b3d4fc; border-radius: 6px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">What does this extension do?</h3>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7;">
        XVE Laravel Kit helps you publish your Laravel website with <strong>zero downtime</strong>.
        Instead of uploading files directly (which can cause errors while visitors are on your site),
        it creates a fresh copy of your code each time you deploy. When the new version is ready,
        it instantly switches over &mdash; your visitors never see a broken page.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 0;">
        It also gives you tools to manage your <code>.env</code> configuration file,
        run Laravel commands, view logs, and roll back to a previous version if something goes wrong.
    </p>
</div>

<!-- ─── Step 1 ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<div style="margin-bottom: 24px; padding: 20px; background: #fff; border: 1px solid #ddd; border-radius: 6px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #2e7d32;">
        <span style="display: inline-block; width: 32px; height: 32px; line-height: 32px; text-align: center; background: #2e7d32; color: #fff; border-radius: 50%; font-size: 16px; margin-right: 10px;">1</span>
        Configure Your Site
    </h3>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7;">
        Go to the <strong>Settings</strong> tab and fill in:
    </p>
    <ul style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 2;">
        <li><strong>Repository URL</strong> &mdash; The address of your code repository. This is usually something like <code>git@github.com:yourname/yourproject.git</code>. Ask your developer if you're not sure.</li>
        <li><strong>Branch</strong> &mdash; Which version of the code to deploy. Usually <code>main</code> or <code>production</code>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 0;">
        The other settings have sensible defaults. Click <strong>Save</strong> and the extension will
        automatically create the folder structure, set file permissions, and generate an SSH key
        for securely downloading your code.
    </p>
</div>

<!-- ─── Step 2 ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<div style="margin-bottom: 24px; padding: 20px; background: #fff; border: 1px solid #ddd; border-radius: 6px;">
    <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #1565c0;">
        <span style="display: inline-block; width: 32px; height: 32px; line-height: 32px; text-align: center; background: #1565c0; color: #fff; border-radius: 50%; font-size: 16px; margin-right: 10px;">2</span>
        Add the Deploy Key
    </h3>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7;">
        After saving, you'll see an <strong>SSH Public Key</strong> on the Settings page.
        This key allows the server to securely download your code from the repository.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7;">
        You need to add this key to your Git hosting provider:
    </p>
    <ul style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 2;">
        <li><strong>GitHub:</strong> Go to your repository &rarr; Settings &rarr; Deploy keys &rarr; Add deploy key. Paste the key and save.</li>
        <li><strong>GitLab:</strong> Go to your project &rarr; Settings &rarr; Repository &rarr; Deploy keys. Paste the key and save.</li>
        <li><strong>Bitbucket:</strong> Go to your repository &rarr; Settings &rarr; Access keys &rarr; Add key. Paste the key and save.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 0;">
        <strong>Tip:</strong> You only need to do this once. The key is read-only &mdash;
